# Widget Design Rules (Flutter)

These rules enforce **predictable UI structure, accessibility compliance, performance stability, and clean separation of concerns**.

Primary screen widgets today live in `apps/eddyscout/lib/screens/` (app shell). Feature `presentation/` layers are the target for new UI owned by a feature package.

All widgets must remain:
- composable
- testable
- accessible
- responsive
- free of business logic

---

# 1. File & Size Constraints

## File Size Limits

- [ ] Target ≤ 300 lines per widget file
- [ ] Hard limit: split if build method becomes unclear or multi-responsibility
- [ ] One primary widget per file
- [ ] Private helper widgets allowed only if tightly scoped

---

## When to Split Widgets

Split when:
- build() exceeds ~80–120 lines
- multiple visual states exist in one widget
- multiple responsibilities are mixed (layout + logic + state handling)
- nested conditional UI becomes hard to follow

---

# 2. Widget Responsibility Rules

## MUST

Widgets are responsible for:
- rendering UI
- reacting to state
- dispatching user intent (callbacks → providers/use cases)

## MUST NOT

Widgets must NOT:
- contain business logic
- perform data fetching directly
- mutate application state directly
- implement domain rules
- coordinate cross-feature logic

---

# 3. Widget Type Selection

## Preferred Patterns

- `ConsumerWidget` → Riverpod-connected UI
- `StatelessWidget` → pure UI with no local state
- `StatefulWidget` → only when strictly required

---

## StatefulWidget Allowed Only For

- animation controllers
- focus nodes
- text editing controllers
- lifecycle-bound UI concerns

## MUST NOT

- use StatefulWidget for business logic
- use StatefulWidget to manage remote state
- use StatefulWidget as a substitute for Riverpod

---

# 4. Composition Rules

## Core Principle

> Prefer composition over inheritance

---

## Rules

- [ ] break UI into small reusable widgets
- [ ] keep widgets single-purpose
- [ ] lift state up only when necessary
- [ ] avoid deeply nested widget trees (max ~5–7 levels where possible)

---

## Anti-Patterns

- giant monolithic screen widgets
- deeply nested `Column > Column > Column`
- conditional UI logic embedded directly in build()
- duplicated UI blocks instead of reusable components

---

# 5. Required UI States (Mandatory)

Every data-driven widget MUST handle all states:

## Required States

- Loading
- Error
- Empty
- Data

---

## Rules

- [ ] loading state must be visible and intentional (not blank screen)
- [ ] error state must be user-friendly (not raw exceptions)
- [ ] empty state must provide guidance or next action
- [ ] data state must be primary default rendering path

---

## Async Handling (Riverpod)

- [ ] always handle `AsyncValue` fully
- [ ] never assume data exists without null safety handling
- [ ] never ignore error state

---

# 6. Accessibility Requirements (MANDATORY)

## Touch Targets

- [ ] minimum 48x48 dp for all interactive elements
- [ ] sufficient spacing between interactive elements

---

## Semantics

- [ ] all icons must have semantic labels
- [ ] all images must have `semanticLabel`
- [ ] custom components must expose semantics via `Semantics`
- [ ] decorative elements must be excluded from semantics tree

---

## Screen Reader Support

- [ ] logical reading order matches visual order
- [ ] meaningful labels for all actions
- [ ] state changes must be announced when relevant

---

## Text Scaling

- [ ] fully support system font scaling (up to 2x)
- [ ] no hardcoded font sizes unless justified
- [ ] no clipped or overflowed text at high scale factors

---

# 7. Performance Rules

- [ ] use `const` constructors wherever possible
- [ ] avoid unnecessary rebuilds
- [ ] keep widget trees shallow where possible
- [ ] use `ListView.builder` for large lists
- [ ] avoid expensive work inside build()

---

## Rebuild Control

- [ ] scope `ref.watch` as narrowly as possible
- [ ] prefer `ref.select` for fine-grained updates
- [ ] split large widgets to isolate rebuild regions

---

# 8. Styling Rules

- [ ] use design system tokens only
- [ ] no hardcoded colors outside theme system
- [ ] no hardcoded spacing values unless defined in constants
- [ ] support light and dark mode natively

---

# 9. Layout Responsiveness

- [ ] use `LayoutBuilder` for adaptive layouts
- [ ] use `Flexible` / `Expanded` instead of fixed widths
- [ ] avoid overflow-prone fixed sizing
- [ ] ensure UI works across phone/tablet/desktop breakpoints

---

# 10. Navigation Rules (UI Layer)

- [ ] navigation must use typed routing system
- [ ] avoid raw string routes in widgets
- [ ] do not embed navigation logic deeply in child widgets
- [ ] prefer navigation intent callbacks passed down from parent

---

# 11. Error Handling Rules

- [ ] errors must be user-readable
- [ ] no stack traces shown in UI
- [ ] include retry actions where appropriate
- [ ] handle offline and timeout states explicitly

---

# 12. Testing Requirements

Each widget should support:

- [ ] rendering tests (default state)
- [ ] loading state tests
- [ ] error state tests
- [ ] interaction tests (tap, input, scroll)

---

# 13. Anti-Patterns (DO NOT DO)

## MUST NOT

- business logic inside widgets
- direct API calls in UI layer
- ignoring loading/error/empty states
- uncontrolled widget growth (>300 lines without split)
- excessive nesting without extraction
- missing semantic labels
- fixed layouts that break responsiveness

---

# 14. Related Cursor Skills

- `form-creation`, `responsive-ui-validation`, `accessibility-review` — `.cursor/skills/`

---

# 15. Validation Checklist

Before committing:

- [ ] widget is within size limits or justified
- [ ] all required states implemented
- [ ] accessibility rules satisfied
- [ ] responsive layout verified
- [ ] performance considerations followed
- [ ] no business logic in UI
- [ ] preflight passes

---

# 15. Output Expectations

When completing widget work:

## Provide

- widget breakdown (if refactored)
- state handling summary
- accessibility notes
- performance considerations
- responsiveness validation